ents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Colonial-era birth, Civil War year death, age ninety-four","body":"Jerusha Parsons was born June 1, 1766 in Stockbridge Massachusetts, when the colonies still answered to George III. She died January 8, 1861 in Victor, Ontario County New York at age ninety-four — three months before Fort Sumter opened the Civil War. Her ninety-four-year life span covered the Revolution, the early Republic, Jacksonian democracy, abolitionism, and the war's first months."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Husband named in Bellamy's Shays' Rebellion novel","body":"Jerusha's husband Ira Seymour Sr. served as deputy sheriff during Shays' Rebellion (1786-1787), siding with the 'aristocrats' Judge Timothy Edwards and Judge Jahleel Woodbridge against the Shays' insurgents — and as deputy sheriff he 'liberated many debtors from the county jail.' Edward Bellamy named him by name in the 1879 historical novel 'The Duke of Stockbridge,' the most-read fictional treatment of the rebellion. Jerusha's marriage thus placed her at the center of the Stockbridge gentry's response to the agrarian revolt."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Husband descended from Hartford co-founder Richard Seymour","body":"Ira Seymour Sr. was the great-great-grandson of Richard Seymour (1596 England - 1655 Norwalk Connecticut) — one of the original founders of Hartford with Thomas Hooker in 1636. Jerusha's marriage thus united two completely independent Hartford-founding family lines through a Berkshire County Massachusetts match, two centuries after the original 1636 settlement. The Seymour-Parsons union is one of the cleaner cases in the tree of Hartford-founder lines reconverging."}],"slug":"jerusha-parsons-1766"},"X00544":{"id":"X00544","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"de